      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating chemical process, a complex cascade of reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars when heated. It's what gives browned foods—like seared steak or toasted bread—their wonderful, complex flavors and aromas. You can really see it happen when you're cooking, and it generally starts kicking in when the temperature climbs above about 285°F (140°C). If you keep the heat up, you'll get those deep, savory, \"browned\" notes.",
